# AP-009 — BDO Application Model

**Status:** Draft v1.0

---

# Abstract

Bitcoin Digital Objects (BDOs) are designed to exist independently of any specific application.

Applications create experiences around Bitcoin Digital Objects.

They do not define their existence.

This document describes the conceptual role of applications within the Bitcoin Digital Objects ecosystem.

---

# Introduction

Applications are where users interact with Bitcoin Digital Objects.

Different applications may provide different experiences while operating on the same object.

The object remains the same.

Only the experience changes.

---

# What is a BDO Application?

A BDO application is any software capable of interacting with Bitcoin Digital Objects.

Examples include:

- wallets
- marketplaces
- games
- social platforms
- ticketing systems
- membership platforms
- identity systems
- collectors
- verification tools
- explorers

Applications are free to specialize in different experiences.

---

# Responsibilities

Applications may:

- display Bitcoin Digital Objects
- verify Bitcoin Digital Objects
- transfer Bitcoin Digital Objects
- interpret capabilities
- present metadata
- organize collections
- build user experiences

Applications should not redefine the object itself.

---

# Ownership Independence

Applications never own Bitcoin Digital Objects.

Users own Bitcoin Digital Objects.

Applications simply provide interfaces.

Changing applications must never change ownership.

---

# Portability

A Bitcoin Digital Object should be usable across multiple compatible applications.

No application should become a mandatory gateway.

Users should remain free to move between applications.

---

# Interpretation

Different applications may interpret the same Bitcoin Digital Object differently.

For example:

Application A may display a collectible.

Application B may unlock premium content.

Application C may grant tournament access.

Application D may verify authenticity only.

The underlying object remains unchanged.

---

# Competition

Applications compete through experiences.

Not through ownership.

Innovation should happen above the ownership layer.

---

# Interoperability

Applications should rely on open specifications.

They should avoid proprietary ownership models whenever possible.

Interoperability enables a healthy ecosystem.

---

# User Freedom

Users should be free to:

- choose their preferred application
- switch applications
- verify independently
- export their objects
- maintain ownership regardless of application

---

# Failure Independence

Applications may disappear.

Bitcoin Digital Objects should remain usable elsewhere.

The disappearance of one application must not destroy digital ownership.

---

# Relationship with Ownership

Applications present ownership.

They do not define ownership.

Ownership exists independently from applications.

---

# Relationship with Issuers

Applications may recognize issuers.

Applications do not become issuers automatically.

These concepts remain independent.

---

# Relationship with Specifications

Applications implement open specifications.

Specifications define interoperability.

Applications define user experiences.

---

# Design Principles

Applications should:

- respect ownership
- support interoperability
- remain replaceable
- encourage innovation
- avoid lock-in

---

# Guiding Principle

> Applications create experiences.

> Bitcoin creates ownership.